// Return-borrow analysis (the return-side dual of the argument-consume fact).
//
// A function "returns a borrow" when its return value is an interior view of a
// PARAMETER returned WITHOUT taking an owning reference — e.g. an iterator
// `.current()` returning the collection's element, the runtime element loaders
// (`__managed_mem_get` / `__managed_mem_cursor_current`) they forward to (real Maxon
// functions whose bodies return a param-derived `load`, classified borrow-returning
// by the same structural leaf rule during the STDLIB BUILD where their bodies are
// present, then persisted in `funcReturnsBorrow` via the cache — NO name allowlist),
// or any `return self.field` / `return param.accessor()` chain. Such a result owns NO
// `+1`: the value it points at is owned by the parameter's collection.
//
// The default classification (`recordCallResultType` -> `callReturnRc1`) assumes
// EVERY direct-call result transfers a `+1` to the caller. That is a LIE for a
// borrow-returning callee, and it breaks container CONSTRUCTION: `Set.init` /
// `Map.init` iterate a borrowed input array (`for elem in arr`) and move each
// `.current()` element into the container's storage. The element-move accounting
// suppresses the element's drop on the assumption a `+1` transfers — but a borrow
// carries none — so the container holds the element with no reference and the
// input array's teardown frees it out from under the container (a destructor-walk
// UAF; the rung-28 over-free).
//
// This pass computes the fact STRUCTURALLY from each callee's body (never by
// callee-name matching, save for the bodyless runtime loader intrinsics noted
// above — the return-side dual of the structural move-model "Concept C") and
// reclassifies borrow-returning call RESULTS by USE:
//   - a result CONSUMED BY A CONTAINER becomes `borrowed` (the container takes its
//     own ref; the source still owns the element); whereas
//   - a result RETURNED by the enclosing function becomes `incomingOwner` so it
//     ACQUIRES its own +1 at the return, handing the caller a genuinely-owned
//     reference (the `Map.get`/`Array.get` element-get contract — see rung-11).
// It runs once on the whole Std module (the per-function inserter cannot see
// callees), AFTER `lowerMaxonToStd` and BEFORE `insertRefcounts`.
//
// Leaf rule — a function's return value is a borrow iff its DEFINING op is:
//   - a `param` op (the parameter's borrowed reference);
//   - a `load_indirect` / `load_byte` (reads memory, mints no ownership); or
//   - a `call` to a function G that itself returns a borrow (forwarding).
// It is NOT a borrow iff the def op is an allocation (`__mm_alloc` / `mrt_alloc*`)
// or a call to a non-borrow-returning function (which hands back an owned `+1`).
// Unknown / value-type-producing defs (arith, const, store) are treated as
// non-borrow: they never produce a managed pointer, so the classification is
// irrelevant and the conservative answer (owns-a-+1) avoids UNDER-counting a real
// owner. The analysis is a fixpoint over the forwarding edges until
// `funcReturnsBorrow` stabilizes.

// Run the analysis: populate `project.funcReturnsBorrow` (fixpoint) then reclassify
// borrow-returning call results across the module. Returns the module unchanged
// (mutates `project.funcReturnsBorrow` and per-function `valueOwnership`).
export function analyzeReturnBorrows(module StdModule, project Project) returns StdModule
	// Identify the element-loader CHAIN-BOUNDARY functions structurally: a function is
	// an element loader iff its body directly calls `__managed_mem_load_sized`, the
	// single sized-managed-element load primitive (see `funcCallsElementLoadPrimitive`).
	// This replaces a hardcoded `{__managed_mem_get, __managed_mem_cursor_current}` name
	// list with the structural fact "routes through the shared load chokepoint" — set-
	// equivalent today (those are the ONLY two callers) and self-extending: a future
	// loader MUST call the primitive to do its element load, so it is recognized with no
	// list edit. Persisted in the cache (v73) for the user build, where these bodies are
	// absent.
	//
	// MUST run BEFORE the borrow fixpoint: the fixpoint's
	// `forwardedBorrowWillBeRetained` consults `calleeIsBorrowFunction`, whose
	// loader EXCLUSION is what keeps a leaf intrinsic-forwarder (`Array.get`,
	// whose returned value forwards `__managed_mem_get`) classified as a PURE
	// borrow. With an empty loader set, the leaf was mispredicted as a
	// retained wrapper and never entered `funcReturnsBorrow` — so no caller
	// reclassified its results, and every stdlib `stack.get(i)` result got a
	// `callReturnRc1` release that stripped the container's element ref (the
	// driftsort run-stack over-release). The detection itself is purely
	// structural (no dependence on the borrow set), so hoisting it is safe.
	for funcIdx in 0 upto module.functions.count() 'eachFuncLoader'
		let func = try module.functions.get(funcIdx) otherwise panic("analyzeReturnBorrows: functions.get OOB at {funcIdx}")
		if func.blockRefs.count() == 0 'empty'
			continue
		end 'empty'
		if funcCallsElementLoadPrimitive(module, func: func) 'isLoader'
			project.funcIsElementLoader.insert(func.name)
		end 'isLoader'
	end 'eachFuncLoader'

	// Seed the BODYLESS runtime element loader: `mrt_managed_list_node_value`
	// reads the node's value slot — a borrow the NODE owns, exactly as
	// `__managed_mem_get` reads an element the MM owns. The structural loops
	// above can't see it (its body lives in runtime.std, not this module), so
	// seed both facts the Maxon-bodied loaders derive structurally:
	//   - `funcIsElementLoader`: it is a chain-boundary loader, so a forwarder
	//     (`ListIterator.current`, `List.first`) stays a PURE borrow-returner
	//     (the wrapper retain lands one level further out, where the borrow
	//     escapes — mirroring `Array.get` over `__managed_mem_get`);
	//   - `funcReturnsBorrow`: its result owns no +1, so the fixpoint's
	//     `valueOwnsPlusOne` doesn't misread a forwarded node-value as owned.
	// Without the seed, `current` was excluded from `funcReturnsBorrow` and
	// `planReturnedBorrowRetains` baked a layout-routed retain into its body;
	// inlined into a concrete caller the retain's +1 had no releasable class
	// (the list-of-structs for-in leak). Both link-leg spellings are seeded.
	project.funcIsElementLoader.insert("mrt_managed_list_node_value")
	project.funcIsElementLoader.insert("stdlib.mrt_managed_list_node_value")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("mrt_managed_list_node_value")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("stdlib.mrt_managed_list_node_value")

	// The node WALKERS likewise return chain-owned borrows (the node pointers
	// the list's links already own), so a function returning a walker result
	// DIRECTLY classifies borrow-returning. (A walker result merged through a
	// loop PHI — `List.walkTo`'s `current = current.next()` — still reads as
	// owning: the phi keeps the conservative owns-+1 answer, since `Array.
	// remove`/`pop` return merge phis whose +1 the transfer machinery supplies.)
	// Mirrors `StdLiveness.calleeReturnsReceiverBorrow`'s walker list.
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("mrt_managed_list_head")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("stdlib.mrt_managed_list_head")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("mrt_managed_list_tail")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("stdlib.mrt_managed_list_tail")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("mrt_managed_list_node_next")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("stdlib.mrt_managed_list_node_next")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("mrt_managed_list_node_prev")
	project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert("stdlib.mrt_managed_list_node_prev")

	// Fixpoint: repeat until no function's return-borrow status flips. Monotonic
	// (once true it stays true), so the loop terminates in <= #functions rounds.
	var changed = true
	while changed 'fixpoint'
		changed = false
		for funcIdx in 0 upto module.functions.count() 'eachFunc'
			let func = try module.functions.get(funcIdx) otherwise panic("analyzeReturnBorrows: functions.get OOB at {funcIdx}")
			if func.blockRefs.count() == 0 'empty'
				continue
			end 'empty'
			if project.funcReturnsBorrow.contains(func.name) 'settled'
				continue
			end 'settled'
			if functionReturnsBorrow(module, func: func, project: project) 'isBorrow'
				project.funcReturnsBorrow.insert(func.name)
				changed = true
			end 'isBorrow'
		end 'eachFunc'
	end 'fixpoint'

	// RECEIVER-INTERIOR sweep (after the borrow fixpoint, so `valueOwnsPlusOne`'s
	// phi trace sees the settled borrow set): a function whose EVERY return value
	// owns no +1 structurally — ignoring the acquired-class / wrapper-retain
	// exemptions that keep +1-handing functions OUT of `funcReturnsBorrow` —
	// returns a pointer INTO its receiver's structure. `List.walkTo` is the
	// motivating member: its loop phi over the chain walkers is acquired (+1 to
	// the caller, so NOT a borrow-returner), but the node's value slot is freed
	// by the chain's teardown, so liveness must extend the receiver list past the
	// node's uses (`recordNavBorrow` consumes the union of this set and
	// `funcReturnsBorrow`). Liveness-only and extend-only: an over-broad entry
	// risks a late release, never a premature free.
	for funcIdx in 0 upto module.functions.count() 'eachFuncInterior'
		let func = try module.functions.get(funcIdx) otherwise panic("analyzeReturnBorrows: functions.get OOB at {funcIdx}")
		if func.blockRefs.count() == 0 'emptyInterior'
			continue
		end 'emptyInterior'
		if project.funcReturnsReceiverInterior.contains(func.name) 'alreadyInterior'
			continue
		end 'alreadyInterior'
		if functionReturnsReceiverInterior(module, func: func, project: project) 'isInterior'
			project.funcReturnsReceiverInterior.insert(func.name)
		end 'isInterior'
	end 'eachFuncInterior'

	// Reclassify: every call RESULT whose callee returns a borrow becomes
	// `borrowed` (it owns no +1) instead of the lowering default `callReturnRc1`.
	// `func` is mutated in place (its `valueOwnership`) and written back.
	for funcIdx in 0 upto module.functions.count() 'eachFuncRC'
		var func = try module.functions.get(funcIdx) otherwise panic("analyzeReturnBorrows: functions.get OOB at {funcIdx}")
		reclassifyBorrowReturnResults(module, func: func, project: project)
		try module.functions.set(funcIdx, value: func) otherwise panic("analyzeReturnBorrows: functions.set OOB at {funcIdx}")
	end 'eachFuncRC'

	return module
end 'analyzeReturnBorrows'

// The receiver-interior dual of `functionReturnsBorrow`: every return value owns
// no +1 STRUCTURALLY (`valueOwnsPlusOne` — allocations and non-borrow calls block
// it), with NO acquired-class / wrapper-retain exemptions: those exemptions
// describe who supplies the caller's +1, not whether the pointee lives inside
// the receiver. Void functions return no interior pointer.
function functionReturnsReceiverInterior(module StdModule, func IrFunction, project Project) returns bool
	let defs = buildValueDefMap(module, func: func)
	var sawReturn = false

	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("functionReturnsReceiverInterior: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("functionReturnsReceiverInterior: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
		let retVal = returnValueOf(term)
		if retVal.present 'isReturn'
			sawReturn = true
			if valueOwnsPlusOne(module, defs: defs, func: func, valueId: retVal.value, project: project) 'ownsPlusOne'
				return false
			end 'ownsPlusOne'
		end 'isReturn'
	end 'eachBlock'

	return sawReturn
end 'functionReturnsReceiverInterior'

// True iff EVERY return terminator of `func` returns a borrow value (per the leaf
// rule). A function with no return value (void) trivially returns no borrow.
function functionReturnsBorrow(module StdModule, func IrFunction, project Project) returns bool
	let defs = buildValueDefMap(module, func: func)
	var sawReturn = false
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("functionReturnsBorrow: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let termIdx = block.terminatorIndex()
		let term = try module.ops.get(termIdx) otherwise panic("functionReturnsBorrow: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
		let retVal = returnValueOf(term)
		if retVal.present 'isReturn'
			sawReturn = true
			// A function returns a borrow iff NONE of its returns OWNS a +1. A return
			// value owns a +1 only when freshly allocated or handed back by a non-
			// borrow-returning call; a load / param / arith-computed scalar / a
			// forwarded borrow-call owns none. (Inverting "every return is a borrow"
			// is more robust: a value-type return — e.g. the bit-extraction `and 1`
			// in `__managed_mem_cursor_current`'s bool path — is an arith result that
			// is provably NOT a managed pointer, so it must not block the borrow
			// classification of the managed-pointer path.)
			//
			// The structural rule alone is NOT the whole story: the inserter HANDS
			// THE CALLER A +1 for two returned-value shapes the structural rule
			// calls borrows, and a function that hands +1 must NOT be in
			// `funcReturnsBorrow` (its call results keep the `callReturnRc1`
			// default and get released):
			//
			//   1. A returned value lowering classified with an ACQUIRED class
			//      (`incomingOwner` / `freshRc0` / `selfReturnBorrow`): the inserter
			//      acquires it at the def or the return (`computeIncomingOwnerAcquire`
			//      rule (a)). Without this, `return self.field` accessors
			//      (`URL.query`) were marked borrow-returning, their call results
			//      reclassified `borrowed` (no release), and the acquire-on-return
			//      +1 leaked on every call.
			//
			//   2. A FORWARDED borrow the reclassify/retain pipeline will repair:
			//      `reclassifyBorrowReturnResults`' wrapper arm flips the returned
			//      forwarded value to `borrowed` and `planReturnedBorrowRetains`
			//      hands the caller a layout-routed +1 (`Map.get`'s element-get
			//      contract). The repair fires regardless of THIS function's set
			//      membership (its gate is the CALLEE's membership), so excluding
			//      the wrapper here exactly matches the +1 it returns.
			if returnedValueClassIsAcquired(func, valueId: retVal.value) 'classAcquired'
				return false
			end 'classAcquired'

			if valueOwnsPlusOne(module, defs: defs, func: func, valueId: retVal.value, project: project) 'ownsPlusOne'
				return false
			end 'ownsPlusOne'

			if forwardedBorrowWillBeRetained(module, defs: defs, func: func, valueId: retVal.value, project: project) 'willRetain'
				return false
			end 'willRetain'
		end 'isReturn'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return sawReturn
end 'functionReturnsBorrow'

// True iff lowering classified `valueId` with a class the inserter ACQUIRES
// (`computeIncomingOwnerAcquire` rule (a) / the def-acquire classes) — a returned
// value of such a class is handed to the caller with a real +1, so the enclosing
// function returns an OWNER, not a borrow. The acquire machinery only fires for
// MANAGED values (`classIsIncomingOwner` / `shouldAcquire` are isManaged-gated),
// so an unmanaged value with a stale acquired class returns NO +1 and must not
// flip its function out of the borrow set (callers would over-release a borrow).
function returnedValueClassIsAcquired(func IrFunction, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	if not func.isValueManaged(valueId) 'notManaged'
		return false
	end 'notManaged'

	return match func.ownershipOfValue(valueId) 'cls'
		freshRc0 or selfReturnBorrow or incomingOwner gives true
		notManaged or callReturnRc1 or borrowed gives false
	end 'cls'
end 'returnedValueClassIsAcquired'

// True iff returned value `valueId` is a forwarded borrow-FUNCTION result the
// reclassify/retain pipeline will hand back with a +1: the wrapper arm of
// `reclassifyBorrowReturnResults` flips it to `borrowed`, and
// `planReturnedBorrowRetains` retains it iff the function's layout resolves —
// guaranteed for a returned type-param value (`funcHasDroppableTypeParam`'s
// returned-borrow arm), else iff some other droppable type-param value forces the
// layout. Mirrors those gates exactly so `funcReturnsBorrow`'s no-+1 meaning holds.
function forwardedBorrowWillBeRetained(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, func IrFunction, valueId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	if not func.isValueManaged(valueId) and not func.isValueTypeParam(valueId) 'notManaged'
		return false
	end 'notManaged'

	let defIdx = try defs.get(valueId) otherwise return false
	let defOp = try module.ops.get(defIdx) otherwise return false

	if not opCallsBorrowFunction(defOp, project: project) 'notForwarded'
		return false
	end 'notForwarded'

	if not func.hasImplicitLayoutParam 'noLayout'
		return false
	end 'noLayout'

	if func.isValueTypeParam(valueId) 'typeParam'
		return true
	end 'typeParam'

	return funcHasDroppableTypeParam(func, returnedValues: returnedValueBits(module, func: func))
end 'forwardedBorrowWillBeRetained'

// The function's returned ValueIds as a BoolArray keyed by ValueId (the shape
// `funcHasDroppableTypeParam` consumes).
function returnedValueBits(module StdModule, func IrFunction) returns BoolArray
	let returned = collectReturnedValues(module, func: func)
	var bits = BoolArray.create()

	for vid in returned 'each'
		while bits.count() <= vid 'grow'
			bits.push(false)
		end 'grow'
		try bits.set(vid, value: true) otherwise panic("returnedValueBits: bits.set OOB after grow")
	end 'each'

	return bits
end 'returnedValueBits'

// An optional ValueId result (no `T?` optional in the codebase — use an explicit
// presence flag, the `BypassTarget`-style idiom).
type RetValueOpt
	export var present as bool
	export var value as ValueId

	export static function some(value ValueId) returns RetValueOpt
		return Self{present: true, value: value}
	end 'some'

	export static function none() returns RetValueOpt
		return Self{present: false, value: i64.max}
	end 'none'
end 'RetValueOpt'

// The returned ValueId of a `ret`/`errorReturn` terminator, else `none`.
function returnValueOf(op StdOp) returns RetValueOpt
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives RetValueOpt.none()
		control gives RetValueOpt.none()
		call(c) gives returnValueOfCall(c)
		memory gives RetValueOpt.none()
		system gives RetValueOpt.none()
	end 'dispatch'
end 'returnValueOf'

function returnValueOfCall(c StdCallOp) returns RetValueOpt
	return match c 'check'
		ret(retValId) gives RetValueOpt.some(retValId)
		call to tailCall gives RetValueOpt.none()
		param gives RetValueOpt.none()
		errorReturn(retValId, _) gives RetValueOpt.some(retValId)
	end 'check'
end 'returnValueOfCall'

// True iff `valueId` (a return value) OWNS a transferable +1 — its defining op is
// a fresh allocation or a call to a NON-borrow-returning function. A load, a
// `param`, an arith-computed scalar, or a forwarded borrow-call owns none. A value
// with no recorded def (e.g. a phi block-arg the fixpoint cannot trace) is treated
// conservatively as owning a +1 (so an untraceable return blocks the borrow
// classification — bias toward "owns a +1", never under-counting a real owner).
function valueOwnsPlusOne(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, func IrFunction, valueId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	// No op def = a BLOCK PARAMETER (phi). Default CONSERVATIVE owns-+1: a phi
	// of not-owners is NOT safely a borrow — `Array.remove`/`pop` return merge
	// phis whose +1 the transfer machinery supplies, and classifying them
	// borrow-returning stripped the caller's release (the remove/pop-transfer
	// mm-ladder regression that reverted the GENERAL phi-tracing experiment).
	// The ONE recognized exception is the all-borrow-CALL merge
	// (`phiMergesOnlyBorrowCallResults`): every incoming is a direct call
	// result of a `funcReturnsBorrow` callee (`List.walkTo`'s loop phi over the
	// seeded `mrt_managed_list_head`/`node_next` walkers) — no arm can be a
	// transfer (+1) source, so the merge is a true borrow. Anything else (a
	// load, a const sentinel, an alloc, a non-borrow call) keeps owns-+1.
	let defIdx = try defs.get(valueId) otherwise 'phiDef'
		var visited = ValueIdArray.create()
		return not phiMergesOnlyBorrowCallResults(module, defs: defs, func: func, phiId: valueId, project: project, visited: visited)
	end 'phiDef'
	let defOp = try module.ops.get(defIdx) otherwise return true
	// A LOAD is the borrow-vs-owner crux: a load whose ADDRESS derives from a
	// parameter is a borrow of the param's pointee (owns no +1 — the iterator
	// `.current()` element). A load from NON-param memory (slab internals, a fresh
	// allocation's interior) is the RESULT of an owning operation reached by
	// pointer — e.g. `__mm_alloc` returns a load of the slab free-list head, which
	// owns the allocated object. So a load owns a +1 UNLESS its address is
	// param-derived. Without this, `__mm_alloc` (and every allocator) is wrongly
	// flagged borrow, stripping the field-store-incref off every `Self{f: T.create()}`.
	if opIsLoad(defOp) 'isLoad'
		// A MODULE-GLOBAL slot read (`load [globalAddr @__data_<var>] + 0`) is a
		// borrow: the `.data` slot is the owner-of-record (it took the +1 at the
		// global store; the exit-time cleanup patch releases it). Without this, a
		// static getter (`return CharacterSet.cachedX`) is judged to return an
		// OWNER, its callers release the "+1" — and the global's occupant is
		// freed out from under the slot (the 181-test global-cleanup
		// over-release). Runtime-internal symbols (slab heads etc.) don't carry
		// the `__data_` Maxon top-level prefix, so allocator loads keep their
		// owner classification.
		if loadIsModuleGlobalSlotRead(module, defs: defs, op: defOp) 'globalSlot'
			return false
		end 'globalSlot'
		var visited = ValueIdArray.create()
		return not loadAddressDerivesFromParam(module, defs: defs, op: defOp, visited: visited)
	end 'isLoad'
	// A POINTER HEADER-OFFSET preserves ownership: `__mm_alloc` returns `slotBase + 32`
	// (the user region just past the 32-byte header) where `slotBase` is the
	// `__slab_alloc` result. An additive op with exactly one CONSTANT operand is a
	// fixed pointer adjustment, not a fresh computation — the result owns a +1 iff the
	// non-constant base does. Bounded to additive-with-one-const so it never turns an
	// index/arith computation (two dynamic operands) into a false owner.
	let offsetBase = additiveConstOffsetBase(module, defs: defs, op: defOp)
	if offsetBase.present 'headerOffset'
		return valueOwnsPlusOne(module, defs: defs, func: func, valueId: offsetBase.value, project: project)
	end 'headerOffset'
	return defOpOwnsPlusOne(defOp, project: project)
end 'valueOwnsPlusOne'

// True iff `phiId` is a block parameter of `func` ALL of whose incoming edge
// values are direct call results of `funcReturnsBorrow` callees — the
// `List.walkTo` shape (`current = chain.head(); current = current.next()` in a
// loop), where every arm is a chain-owned node borrow. Loop-carried self-edges
// and mutually-phi incomings recurse with a visited set (a cycle contributes no
// +1). Returns false for anything else, INCLUDING a phi with no incoming edges
// (nothing proves it a borrow).
function phiMergesOnlyBorrowCallResults(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, func IrFunction, phiId ValueId, project Project, visited ValueIdArray) returns bool
	if valueIdArrayContainsRB(visited, vid: phiId) 'cycle'
		return true
	end 'cycle'
	visited.push(phiId)

	let (found, phiBlockId, argIdx) = findBlockArgPosition(module, func: func, valueId: phiId)
	if not found 'notBlockArg'
		return false
	end 'notBlockArg'

	var sawIncoming = false
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("phiMergesOnlyBorrowCallResults: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("phiMergesOnlyBorrowCallResults: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
		let edges = branchArgsInto(term, targetBlockId: phiBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
		for incoming in edges 'eachIncoming'
			sawIncoming = true
			if incoming == phiId 'selfEdge'
				continue
			end 'selfEdge'
			if not incomingIsBorrowCallOrPhi(module, defs: defs, func: func, incoming: incoming, project: project, visited: visited) 'notBorrow'
				return false
			end 'notBorrow'
		end 'eachIncoming'
	end 'eachBlock'

	return sawIncoming
end 'phiMergesOnlyBorrowCallResults'

// One incoming of the all-borrow merge: a direct `funcReturnsBorrow`-callee call
// result, or itself a phi that recursively satisfies the same rule.
function incomingIsBorrowCallOrPhi(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, func IrFunction, incoming ValueId, project Project, visited ValueIdArray) returns bool
	let inDefIdx = try defs.get(incoming) otherwise 'incomingPhi'
		return phiMergesOnlyBorrowCallResults(module, defs: defs, func: func, phiId: incoming, project: project, visited: visited)
	end 'incomingPhi'
	let inOp = try module.ops.get(inDefIdx) otherwise return false
	return opIsBorrowSetCall(inOp, project: project)
end 'incomingIsBorrowCallOrPhi'

// True iff `op` is a static call/tryCall whose callee is in `funcReturnsBorrow`.
// Plain set membership — the loader chain-boundary exclusion
// (`calleeIsBorrowFunction`) is irrelevant here: a loader result merged through
// a phi is still a borrow for +1-counting purposes.
function opIsBorrowSetCall(op StdOp, project Project) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callIsBorrowSetCall(c, project: project)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsBorrowSetCall'

function callIsBorrowSetCall(c StdCallOp, project Project) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, _) gives project.funcReturnsBorrow.contains(callee)
		tryCall(_, callee, _, _) gives project.funcReturnsBorrow.contains(callee)
		ret gives false
		indirectCall to tailCall gives false
		param gives false
		errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callIsBorrowSetCall'

// Locate `valueId` among the block parameters of `func`: returns
// `(true, blockId, argIndex)` on a hit, `(false, 0, 0)` otherwise.
function findBlockArgPosition(module StdModule, func IrFunction, valueId ValueId) returns (bool, BlockId, NodeIndex)
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("findBlockArgPosition: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for i in 0 upto block.blockArgs.count() 'eachArg'
			let arg = try block.blockArgs.get(i) otherwise panic("findBlockArgPosition: blockArgs.get({i}) OOB despite bounds")
			if arg.valueId == valueId 'hit'
				return (true, block.id, i)
			end 'hit'
		end 'eachArg'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return (false, 0, 0)
end 'findBlockArgPosition'

// The values a terminator passes into `targetBlockId`'s block-arg `argIdx` —
// zero, one, or (for a condBr whose both arms hit the target) two entries.
function branchArgsInto(term StdOp, targetBlockId BlockId, argIdx NodeIndex) returns ValueIdArray
	var out = ValueIdArray.create()
	match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) then collectControlArgsInto(cf, targetBlockId: targetBlockId, argIdx: argIdx, out: out)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		call then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
		system then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
	return out
end 'branchArgsInto'

function collectControlArgsInto(cf StdControlOp, targetBlockId BlockId, argIdx NodeIndex, out ValueIdArray)
	match cf 'check'
		br(target, argIds) then appendEdgeArg(out, target: target, argIds: argIds, targetBlockId: targetBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
		condBr(_, thenTarget, thenArgIds, elseTarget, elseArgIds) then appendCondBrEdgeArgs(out, thenTarget: thenTarget, thenArgIds: thenArgIds, elseTarget: elseTarget, elseArgIds: elseArgIds, targetBlockId: targetBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
	end 'check'
end 'collectControlArgsInto'

function appendCondBrEdgeArgs(out ValueIdArray, thenTarget BlockId, thenArgIds ValueIdArray, elseTarget BlockId, elseArgIds ValueIdArray, targetBlockId BlockId, argIdx NodeIndex)
	appendEdgeArg(out, target: thenTarget, argIds: thenArgIds, targetBlockId: targetBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
	appendEdgeArg(out, target: elseTarget, argIds: elseArgIds, targetBlockId: targetBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
end 'appendCondBrEdgeArgs'

function appendEdgeArg(out ValueIdArray, target BlockId, argIds ValueIdArray, targetBlockId BlockId, argIdx NodeIndex)
	if target != targetBlockId 'otherTarget'
		return
	end 'otherTarget'
	let vid = try argIds.get(argIdx) otherwise return
	out.push(vid)
end 'appendEdgeArg'

// Local contains helper (the InsertRefcounts `valueIdArrayContains` is
// module-private to that file).
function valueIdArrayContainsRB(arr ValueIdArray, vid ValueId) returns bool
	for v in arr 'each'
		if v == vid 'hit'
			return true
		end 'hit'
	end 'each'
	return false
end 'valueIdArrayContainsRB'

// If `op` is an additive binary op (`addI64`/`subI64`) with exactly one CONSTANT
// operand, the ValueId of its non-constant base operand (a fixed pointer offset);
// else `none`. The base whose ownership the offset result inherits (see
// `valueOwnsPlusOne`'s header-offset case).
function additiveConstOffsetBase(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, op StdOp) returns RetValueOpt
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith(a) gives additiveConstOffsetBaseArith(a, module: module, defs: defs)
		control gives RetValueOpt.none()
		call gives RetValueOpt.none()
		memory gives RetValueOpt.none()
		system gives RetValueOpt.none()
	end 'dispatch'
end 'additiveConstOffsetBase'

function additiveConstOffsetBaseArith(a StdArithOp, module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap) returns RetValueOpt
	return match a 'check'
		const gives RetValueOpt.none()
		unary gives RetValueOpt.none()
		binary(b) gives additiveConstOffsetBaseBinary(b, module: module, defs: defs)
	end 'check'
end 'additiveConstOffsetBaseArith'

function additiveConstOffsetBaseBinary(b StdArithBinaryOp, module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap) returns RetValueOpt
	let kind = additiveOpcodeKind(b.opcode)
	if kind == (AdditiveKind.notAdditive) 'notAdd'
		return RetValueOpt.none()
	end 'notAdd'
	let leftConst = valueIsConstant(module, defs: defs, valueId: b.leftId)
	let rightConst = valueIsConstant(module, defs: defs, valueId: b.rightId)
	// `subI64` is base - const (the const must be the right operand to be an offset);
	// `addI64` commutes, so either operand may be the const. Exactly one constant.
	if rightConst and not leftConst 'baseLeft'
		return RetValueOpt.some(b.leftId)
	end 'baseLeft'
	if leftConst and not rightConst and kind == (AdditiveKind.commutativeAdd) 'baseRight'
		return RetValueOpt.some(b.rightId)
	end 'baseRight'
	return RetValueOpt.none()
end 'additiveConstOffsetBaseBinary'

// Whether a binary opcode is an additive pointer-offset, and if so whether it
// commutes (an `addI64` const may be on either side; a `subI64` const must be the
// subtrahend on the right).
enum AdditiveKind
	notAdditive
	commutativeAdd
	subtractRight
end 'AdditiveKind'

function additiveOpcodeKind(opcode StdArithBinaryOpcode) returns AdditiveKind
	return match opcode 'check'
		addI64 gives AdditiveKind.commutativeAdd
		subI64 gives AdditiveKind.subtractRight
		mulI64 to cmpF64Ge gives AdditiveKind.notAdditive
	end 'check'
end 'additiveOpcodeKind'

// True iff `valueId` is defined by an integer-constant op (`constI64`).
function valueIsConstant(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	let defIdx = try defs.get(valueId) otherwise return false
	let defOp = try module.ops.get(defIdx) otherwise return false
	return match defOp 'dispatch'
		arith(a) gives arithOpIsConst(a)
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'valueIsConstant'

function arithOpIsConst(a StdArithOp) returns bool
	return match a 'check'
		const gives true
		unary gives false
		binary gives false
	end 'check'
end 'arithOpIsConst'

// True iff `op` is a memory-reading load (`load_indirect`/`load_byte`).
function opIsLoad(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system(s) gives sysOpIsLoad(s)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsLoad'

function sysOpIsLoad(s StdSystemOp) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		globalAddr to storeByte gives false
		loadByte gives true
		osExit to loadFramePtr gives false
		loadIndirect gives true
		funcAddr to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysOpIsLoad'

// True iff the ADDRESS operand of load `op` is PARAM-ROOTED (the load reads the
// parameter's pointee — a borrow), as opposed to global/alloc-rooted (owns a +1).
// See `addressIsParamRooted` for the global-root discriminator that distinguishes a
// param deref-base from a param used as an index offset into a global. `visited`
// guards against cycles (a phi-fed address).
function loadAddressDerivesFromParam(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, op StdOp, visited ValueIdArray) returns bool
	let addrId = loadAddressId(op)
	if addrId == (i64.max) 'noAddr'
		return false
	end 'noAddr'
	return addressIsParamRooted(module, defs: defs, valueId: addrId, visited: visited)
end 'loadAddressDerivesFromParam'

// True iff `op` is a `loadIndirect` at offset 0 whose address is DIRECTLY a
// `globalAddr` of a Maxon module-global `.data` slot (`__data_<topLevelVar>`,
// the `dataSymbolName` shape `lowerGlobalLoad` emits). The slot owns its
// occupant, so the loaded value is a borrow. Runtime `.data` symbols (slab
// state etc.) have their own un-prefixed names and are deliberately excluded.
function loadIsModuleGlobalSlotRead(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, op StdOp) returns bool
	let slot = match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
		control gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
		call gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
		memory gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
		system(s) gives globalSlotLoadOfSys(s)
	end 'dispatch'
	if not slot.present 'notSlotLoad'
		return false
	end 'notSlotLoad'
	let addrDefIdx = try defs.get(slot.addrId) otherwise return false
	let addrDef = try module.ops.get(addrDefIdx) otherwise return false
	return opIsModuleGlobalAddr(addrDef)
end 'loadIsModuleGlobalSlotRead'

type GlobalSlotLoad
	export let present as bool
	export let addrId as ValueId

	export static function none() returns GlobalSlotLoad
		return Self{present: false, addrId: 0}
	end 'none'

	export static function some(addrId ValueId) returns GlobalSlotLoad
		return Self{present: true, addrId: addrId}
	end 'some'
end 'GlobalSlotLoad'

function globalSlotLoadOfSys(s StdSystemOp) returns GlobalSlotLoad
	return match s 'check'
		loadIndirect(_, addrId, offset, _, _, _) gives (GlobalSlotLoad.some(addrId) if offset == 0 else GlobalSlotLoad.none())
		globalAddr to storeByte gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
		loadByte gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
		osExit to loadFramePtr gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
		funcAddr to dropTypeParam gives GlobalSlotLoad.none()
	end 'check'
end 'globalSlotLoadOfSys'

function opIsModuleGlobalAddr(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system(s) gives sysOpIsModuleGlobalAddr(s)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsModuleGlobalAddr'

function sysOpIsModuleGlobalAddr(s StdSystemOp) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		globalAddr(_, name) gives name.startsWith("__data_")
		memcpy to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysOpIsModuleGlobalAddr'

// The address (base) operand of a load op, or `i64.max` sentinel for a non-load.
function loadAddressId(op StdOp) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives i64.max
		control gives i64.max
		call gives i64.max
		memory gives i64.max
		system(s) gives sysLoadAddressId(s)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'loadAddressId'

function sysLoadAddressId(s StdSystemOp) returns ValueId
	return match s 'check'
		loadIndirect(_, addrId, _, _, _, _) gives addrId
		loadByte(_, baseId, _) gives baseId
		globalAddr to storeByte gives i64.max
		osExit to loadFramePtr gives i64.max
		funcAddr to dropTypeParam gives i64.max
	end 'check'
end 'sysLoadAddressId'

// True iff `valueId` is a PARAM-ROOTED address — its dereferenced base is a
// parameter (passed directly, or reached by loading THROUGH param memory), NOT
// merely a parameter used as an additive INDEX OFFSET into a global-rooted base.
// Walks the def chain through loads (the loaded value carries the param-ness of its
// address) and arith (address computation). Stops at calls / allocations (not
// param-rooted). `visited` bounds the walk.
//
// THE GLOBAL-ROOT DISCRIMINATOR. An arith address whose operand chain reaches a
// `globalAddr` op is global-rooted REGARDLESS of any sibling param offset — so a
// load through it owns a +1, not a borrow. This is what separates the slab
// allocator from an element accessor: `__slab_alloc_class` computes
// `mcacheSlot = globalAddr(__slab_mcache_base) + shard*STRIDE + (classIdx shl 3)`
// and loads through it — `classIdx` (a param) is only an additive index into a
// GLOBAL base, so the loaded free-list head OWNS a +1 (a fresh allocation). Without
// the discriminator, the param-in-the-arith wrongly flagged the allocator's result
// a borrow, stripping the field-store-incref off every `Self{f: T.create()}` and
// forcing the (now-removed) `calleeIsAllocation` name list. Conversely, the element
// loaders (`__managed_mem_get`/`cursor_current`) root their address at the param
// itself — `buffer = loadIndirect(self); load(buffer + idx*elemSize)` — with NO
// `globalAddr` in the chain, so they correctly STAY borrows.
function addressIsParamRooted(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, valueId ValueId, visited ValueIdArray) returns bool
	if valueIdArrayContains(visited, vid: valueId) 'seen'
		return false
	end 'seen'
	visited.push(valueId)
	let defIdx = try defs.get(valueId) otherwise return false
	let defOp = try module.ops.get(defIdx) otherwise return false
	if opIsParam(defOp) 'param'
		return true
	end 'param'
	if opIsGlobalAddr(defOp) 'global'
		return false
	end 'global'
	if opIsLoad(defOp) 'load'
		let addrId = loadAddressId(defOp)
		if addrId == (i64.max) 'noAddr'
			return false
		end 'noAddr'
		return addressIsParamRooted(module, defs: defs, valueId: addrId, visited: visited)
	end 'load'
	if opIsArith(defOp) 'arith'
		// A global-rooted operand dominates: the address is an offset INTO a global,
		// not a deref of a param, so no operand's param-ness makes it a borrow.
		if anyOperandRootsInGlobal(module, defs: defs, op: defOp) 'globalRooted'
			return false
		end 'globalRooted'
		let operands = extractStdOpOperands(defOp)
		for readId in operands.readIds 'eachOperand'
			if addressIsParamRooted(module, defs: defs, valueId: readId, visited: visited) 'derives'
				return true
			end 'derives'
		end 'eachOperand'
		return false
	end 'arith'
	return false
end 'addressIsParamRooted'

// True iff any operand of arith `op` transitively roots in a `globalAddr` op
// (through loads + further arith). The global-root marker for `addressIsParamRooted`:
// an address expression containing a global base is an offset into that global, never
// a borrow of a parameter's pointee. Each operand gets its own fresh `visited` bound
// (a separate cycle guard per operand subtree).
function anyOperandRootsInGlobal(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, op StdOp) returns bool
	let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
	for readId in operands.readIds 'eachOperand'
		var seen = ValueIdArray.create()
		if valueRootsInGlobal(module, defs: defs, valueId: readId, visited: seen) 'global'
			return true
		end 'global'
	end 'eachOperand'
	return false
end 'anyOperandRootsInGlobal'

// True iff `valueId` transitively roots in a `globalAddr` op, walking through loads
// (the loaded value carries the global-ness of its address) and arith operands.
function valueRootsInGlobal(module StdModule, defs ValueDefMap, valueId ValueId, visited ValueIdArray) returns bool
	if valueIdArrayContains(visited, vid: valueId) 'seen'
		return false
	end 'seen'
	visited.push(valueId)
	let defIdx = try defs.get(valueId) otherwise return false
	let defOp = try module.ops.get(defIdx) otherwise return false
	if opIsGlobalAddr(defOp) 'global'
		return true
	end 'global'
	if opIsLoad(defOp) 'load'
		let addrId = loadAddressId(defOp)
		if addrId == (i64.max) 'noAddr'
			return false
		end 'noAddr'
		return valueRootsInGlobal(module, defs: defs, valueId: addrId, visited: visited)
	end 'load'
	if opIsArith(defOp) 'arith'
		let operands = extractStdOpOperands(defOp)
		for readId in operands.readIds 'eachOperand'
			if valueRootsInGlobal(module, defs: defs, valueId: readId, visited: visited) 'roots'
				return true
			end 'roots'
		end 'eachOperand'
		return false
	end 'arith'
	return false
end 'valueRootsInGlobal'

// True iff `op` is a `globalAddr` system op (the address of a named data global —
// the base of slab/runtime global state, never a parameter's pointee).
function opIsGlobalAddr(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system(s) gives sysOpIsGlobalAddr(s)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsGlobalAddr'

function sysOpIsGlobalAddr(s StdSystemOp) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		globalAddr gives true
		memcpy to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysOpIsGlobalAddr'

// True iff `op` is a `param` op.
function opIsParam(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call(c) gives callOpIsParam(c)
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsParam'

function callOpIsParam(c StdCallOp) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		ret gives false
		call to tailCall gives false
		param gives true
		errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callOpIsParam'

// True iff `op` is an arithmetic op (address computation / scalar).
function opIsArith(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives true
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsArith'

// Classify a value's DEFINING op as owning a +1 (true) or not (false). A call to a
// non-borrow-returning callee mints/forwards an owned +1; an OS-page allocation
// syscall (`osAllocPages`/`osAllocPagesLarge`) mints fresh OS memory the caller
// owns. Params, arith, stores, etc. do not. (Loads are handled separately in
// `valueOwnsPlusOne` by address provenance; additive header-offsets there too.)
function defOpOwnsPlusOne(op StdOp, project Project) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call(c) gives callOpOwnsPlusOne(c, project: project)
		memory gives false
		system(s) gives sysOpOwnsPlusOne(s)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'defOpOwnsPlusOne'

// True iff `s` is an OS-page allocation syscall — it mints fresh, owned memory
// (`__slab_os_direct_alloc` returns `osAllocPages(...)` directly). Every other
// system op (loads, stores, atomics, descriptor reads) owns no +1.
function sysOpOwnsPlusOne(s StdSystemOp) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		globalAddr to drop gives false
		osAllocPages gives true
		osAllocPagesLarge gives true
		osFreePages to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysOpOwnsPlusOne'

// A `param` op (borrowed param ref), a borrow-returning call, or an allocation
// that is itself a borrow (never — allocs own a +1) do NOT own a +1 here. A direct
// `call`/`tryCall` to a NON-borrow-returning function owns the call's +1. An
// indirect/witness call is treated conservatively as owning a +1 (unknown callee).
function callOpOwnsPlusOne(c StdCallOp, project Project) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		ret gives false
		call(_, callee, _) gives not calleeReturnsBorrow(callee, project: project)
		tryCall(_, callee, _, _) gives not calleeReturnsBorrow(callee, project: project)
		indirectCall to tailCall gives true
		param gives false
		errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callOpOwnsPlusOne'

// True iff a call to `callee` yields a borrow (owns no +1) — consult the structural
// fixpoint set. FULLY STRUCTURAL — no callee-name allowlist whatsoever, including for
// allocators. The allocator family (`__mm_alloc` → `__slab_alloc` → `__slab_alloc_class`
// / `__slab_os_direct_alloc`) is classified owns-+1 by the leaf rule directly:
// `__slab_alloc_class` loads through a `globalAddr(__slab_mcache_base)`-rooted address
// (the global-root discriminator in `addressIsParamRooted`), `__slab_os_direct_alloc`
// returns an `osAllocPages` syscall result (`sysOpOwnsPlusOne`), and `__mm_alloc`'s
// `slotBase + 32` header-offset inherits its base's ownership (`additiveConstOffsetBase`).
// So no allocator ever enters `funcReturnsBorrow`, and a call to one here correctly
// reports NOT-a-borrow with no name check. The bodyless element-loader intrinsics
// (`__managed_mem_get` / `__managed_mem_cursor_current`) ARE real Maxon functions whose
// bodies return a param-rooted `load`; `analyzeReturnBorrows` runs over the stdlib during
// the STDLIB BUILD (where their bodies are present), classifies them borrow-returning by
// that same leaf rule, and persists the result in `funcReturnsBorrow` (cache v72). The
// user build restores it, so a call to `__managed_mem_get` here is recognized from the
// cached structural fact, NOT a hardcoded name list a future intrinsic would silently
// need adding to.
function calleeReturnsBorrow(callee String, project Project) returns bool
	return project.funcReturnsBorrow.contains(callee)
end 'calleeReturnsBorrow'

// Reclassify each borrow-returning call RESULT in `func` to `OwnershipClass.borrowed`
// (it owns no +1, unlike the lowering default `callReturnRc1`'s assumption of a
// transferred +1). Only managed / type-parameter call results with a USE the default
// mishandles are touched:
//
//   CONTAINER-CONSUMED. The result is moved into a container's element storage. The
//     container must take its OWN ref (the inserter's
//     `planBorrowedElementContainerRetains`); the source collection still owns the
//     element. (The original rung-28 over-free fix.) Applies to ANY borrow-returning
//     callee, including the iterator `.current()` chain (cursor_current).
//
//   FORWARDED THROUGH A WRAPPER. The result of a borrow-returning stdlib FUNCTION is
//     FORWARDED as this function's own return value (`Map.get` returns the borrow from
//     `values.get(...)` — a call to `Array.get`). Returned as-is, the caller (which
//     treats the result as `callReturnRc1`) consumes a +1 the borrow never owned and
//     double-frees once the source collection's teardown frees the element (the
//     `Map<K,Box>` get-borrow-after-free). Marking it `borrowed` makes the inserter's
//     `planReturnedBorrowRetains` emit a layout-routed retain so the WRAPPER hands its
//     caller a genuinely-owned +1; the caller's default `callReturnRc1` consumes it.
//
//     The repair is gated to a borrow-returning stdlib FUNCTION callee, NOT a bodyless
//     borrow INTRINSIC (`__managed_mem_get` / `__managed_mem_cursor_current`). A leaf
//     accessor whose return is the intrinsic directly (`Array.get`, `Iterator.current`)
//     must KEEP returning a borrow: it is the form called INTERNALLY as a transient
//     view (`Map.findSlot`/`contains` compare `keys.get(i)` without decreffing; the
//     loop body reads `it.current()` without owning it), and retaining it there would
//     leak (the source still owns the element). Repairing only the wrapper layer —
//     the boundary where the value ESCAPES to an external keeper — fixes the kept-get
//     contract without disturbing those internal borrows, and fires EXACTLY ONCE per
//     forwarding chain (the leaf stays a borrow, the wrapper retains once). A direct
//     user `arr.get(i)` kept past the array's life is repaired the same way at ITS
//     enclosing function (which forwards the stdlib `Array.get`) — the rung-11 contract
//     (proven for both the inlined and this non-inlined wrapper path).
//
// NARROWING (blast-radius control): a borrow-returning result that is STORED
// (captured by a closure, stored into a non-container field) is left untouched —
// reclassifying those was measured to regress (`ownership/closure-captures-
// borrow`): the store-side machinery expects the stored value's class to carry
// the +1 it moves. The three reclassified shapes (container-consumed,
// wrapper-forwarded, transient-read-only) each have matching inserter handling
// for the borrowed class.
function reclassifyBorrowReturnResults(module StdModule, func IrFunction, project Project)
	let returned = collectReturnedValues(module, func: func)
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("reclassifyBorrowReturnResults: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("reclassifyBorrowReturnResults: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let res = borrowReturningCallResult(op, project: project)
			if res.present 'borrowResult'
				// Only a MANAGED result can be a refcounted borrow; a non-managed
				// (primitive) result ignores the class. A type-parameter result is
				// managed-at-runtime via its layout, so it is reclassified too.
				let managed = func.isValueManaged(res.value) or func.isValueTypeParam(res.value)
				let consumed = resultConsumedByContainer(module, func: func, resultId: res.value, project: project)
				let forwarded = opCallsBorrowFunction(op, project: project) and valueIdArrayContains(returned, vid: res.value)
				// THIRD case: a borrow result used ONLY TRANSIENTLY — never stored
				// (heap field / slot / closure capture), never consumed by a container
				// mutator, never returned; all uses are plain reads (a compare, a
				// print, a field load). The default `callReturnRc1` plants a last-use
				// RELEASE for a +1 the borrow never owned, stripping the container's
				// own reference off the element (the `Log.fired` scan-loop
				// over-release: each non-inlined `ArrayIterator.current` read decref'd
				// the live element to 0 under the still-live array). `borrowed` (no
				// acquire, no release) is exactly right for a transient read; the
				// borrow's validity across its uses is the borrow-liveness machinery's
				// job either way. Stored/captured borrows stay untouched (the measured
				// `ownership/closure-captures-borrow` regression of a blanket flip).
				let transientOnly = not valueIdArrayContains(returned, vid: res.value) and not borrowResultIsStoredAnywhere(module, func: func, resultId: res.value)
				if managed and (consumed or forwarded or transientOnly) 'reclassify'
					func.setValueOwnership(res.value, cls: OwnershipClass.borrowed)
				end 'reclassify'
			end 'borrowResult'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'reclassifyBorrowReturnResults'

// True iff `op` is a direct/try call to a borrow-returning stdlib FUNCTION (one with
// a Maxon body, in `funcReturnsBorrow`) — NOT a bodyless borrow intrinsic. This is
// the wrapper-forwarding case repaired by `planReturnedBorrowRetains`: the leaf
// intrinsic-returning accessors (`Array.get`/`Iterator.current`) stay borrows so
// their internal transient-borrow callers are undisturbed.
function opCallsBorrowFunction(op StdOp, project Project) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call(c) gives callIsBorrowFunction(c, project: project)
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opCallsBorrowFunction'

function callIsBorrowFunction(c StdCallOp, project Project) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		ret gives false
		call(_, callee, _) gives calleeIsBorrowFunction(callee, project: project)
		tryCall(_, callee, _, _) gives calleeIsBorrowFunction(callee, project: project)
		indirectCall to tailCall gives false
		param gives false
		errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callIsBorrowFunction'

// True iff `callee` is a borrow-returning WRAPPER FUNCTION (in the cached/fixpoint set)
// whose result the enclosing function should retain when it FORWARDS it — i.e. NOT one
// of the element-loader leaf intrinsics. This is the wrapper-retain boundary: the retain
// that converts a forwarded borrow into a genuinely-owned `+1` must fire EXACTLY ONCE
// per forwarding chain, at the OUTER wrapper. The chain is always
// `__managed_mem_load_sized`(load) ← `__managed_mem_get`(fwd) ← `Array.get` ← `Map.get`;
// excluding the `__managed_mem_*` element-loaders here makes the FIRST stdlib wrapper
// (`Array.get`) NOT retain (its forwardee is an excluded loader) while the next
// (`Map.get`) DOES — net one retain, where the borrow escapes to the user.
//
// The boundary marks WHERE the chain's retain lands (the retain-exactly-once semantic),
// not whether a callee returns a borrow. It is now STRUCTURAL: the excluded loaders are
// exactly the functions that route through the shared `__managed_mem_load_sized` load
// primitive (`funcIsElementLoader`, computed during the stdlib build, cached v73). The
// loaders are bodied forwarders indistinguishable from the wrappers by leaf-vs-forwarder
// / has-body tests — but the wrappers call the LOADERS while the loaders call the load
// PRIMITIVE, so "calls the primitive" cleanly separates them. Dropping the exclusion
// DOUBLE-retains the get-borrow → leak (verified). A FUTURE element-loader added to
// `lowerManagedMemBuiltin` is recognized automatically: it MUST call the primitive to do
// its element load, so no list edit is needed.
//
// RELATED (not a synced copy): `StdLiveness.calleeReturnsReceiverBorrow` marks the
// same CONCEPT — a result that is an interior borrow of arg 0 — for the liveness
// extension, but its membership deliberately DIFFERS: it adds the list-node walkers
// (`mrt_managed_list_*`) and omits `__managed_mem_get` (the element-get's live range
// is already covered by other edges). It remains a name list (those walkers are
// bodyless runtime primitives with no in-module body to scan).
function calleeIsBorrowFunction(callee String, project Project) returns bool
	if isElementLoaderIntrinsic(callee, project: project) 'loader'
		return false
	end 'loader'
	return project.funcReturnsBorrow.contains(callee)
end 'calleeIsBorrowFunction'

// True iff `callee` is an element-loader CHAIN-BOUNDARY function — one that routes
// through the shared sized-managed-element load primitive (`funcCallsElementLoadPrimitive`),
// computed structurally during the stdlib build and persisted in `funcIsElementLoader`
// (cache v73). Replaces a hardcoded name list: a future `__managed_mem_*` loader is
// recognized automatically because it MUST call the load primitive, with no list edit.
// Bare and `stdlib.`-qualified spellings both land in the set (the function's own name
// as it appears in the module). The cache restore also seeds both spellings.
function isElementLoaderIntrinsic(callee String, project Project) returns bool
	return project.funcIsElementLoader.contains(callee)
end 'isElementLoaderIntrinsic'

// True iff `func`'s body directly calls `__managed_mem_load_sized` — the single
// element-size-dispatched managed-pointer load primitive in the runtime. It is called
// ONLY by the element loaders (`__managed_mem_get` / `__managed_mem_cursor_current`),
// so "calls it" is the structural signature of an element-loader chain bottom: the layer
// whose return is a RAW receiver-borrow (a load of the receiver's interior), below which
// the wrapper-retain must NOT fire. Wrappers (`Array.get` / `Map.get`) call the loaders,
// not the primitive, so they are correctly excluded.
function funcCallsElementLoadPrimitive(module StdModule, func IrFunction) returns bool
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("funcCallsElementLoadPrimitive: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("funcCallsElementLoadPrimitive: opIdx not in module.ops")
			if opCallsElementLoadPrimitive(op) 'calls'
				return true
			end 'calls'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'funcCallsElementLoadPrimitive'

function opCallsElementLoadPrimitive(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call(c) gives callTargetsElementLoadPrimitive(c)
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opCallsElementLoadPrimitive'

function callTargetsElementLoadPrimitive(c StdCallOp) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		ret gives false
		call(_, callee, _) gives calleeIsElementLoadPrimitive(callee)
		tryCall(_, callee, _, _) gives calleeIsElementLoadPrimitive(callee)
		indirectCall to tailCall gives false
		param gives false
		errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callTargetsElementLoadPrimitive'

// True iff `callee` is the sized-managed-element load primitive. This is the ONE
// anchored runtime name in the boundary detection — a single chokepoint function, not a
// growable list. Both link-leg spellings are matched.
function calleeIsElementLoadPrimitive(callee String) returns bool
	return callee == "stdlib.__managed_mem_load_sized" or callee == "__managed_mem_load_sized"
end 'calleeIsElementLoadPrimitive'

// The set of ValueIds returned by any `ret`/`errorReturn` terminator of `func` —
// the values whose +1 (once they own one) transfers to the caller. Used to detect
// a get-intrinsic borrow result the enclosing function FORWARDS as its own return
// value, so the inserter retains it into a genuinely-owned +1.
function collectReturnedValues(module StdModule, func IrFunction) returns ValueIdArray
	var returned = ValueIdArray.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectReturnedValues: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("collectReturnedValues: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
		let retVal = returnValueOf(term)
		if retVal.present 'isReturn'
			returned.push(retVal.value)
		end 'isReturn'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return returned
end 'collectReturnedValues'

// True iff any op in `func` STORES `resultId` — into a heap field
// (`storeIndirect` as the VALUE operand), a stack slot (`storeSlot`, including
// closure-captured address-taken slots), or a global. A stored borrow escapes
// into an owner whose teardown expects a real +1, so the transient-read
// reclassification must not touch it.
function borrowResultIsStoredAnywhere(module StdModule, func IrFunction, resultId ValueId) returns bool
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("borrowResultIsStoredAnywhere: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("borrowResultIsStoredAnywhere: opIdx not in module.ops")
			if opStoresValue(op, vid: resultId) 'stored'
				return true
			end 'stored'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'borrowResultIsStoredAnywhere'

function opStoresValue(op StdOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory(m) gives memOpStoresValue(m, vid: vid)
		system(s) gives sysOpStoresValue(s, vid: vid)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opStoresValue'

function memOpStoresValue(m StdMemoryOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match m 'check'
		storeSlot(_, valueId) gives valueId == vid
		loadSlot gives false
	end 'check'
end 'memOpStoresValue'

function sysOpStoresValue(s StdSystemOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		storeIndirect(_, _, valueId, _, _) gives valueId == vid
		globalAddr to loadByte gives false
		osExit to osWrite gives false
		free gives false
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr gives false
		funcAddr gives false
		loadIndirect gives false
		drop gives false
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir gives false
		atomicInc to osLockRelease gives false
		boxValue to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysOpStoresValue'

// True iff `resultId` is used anywhere in `func` as a non-self element argument to
// a CONTAINER MUTATOR call (`Set.insert`/`Map.insert`/`Array.push`/…) — i.e. it is
// MOVED into a container's element storage. A consumed borrow-returning result is
// reclassified `borrowed` so the inserter's `planBorrowedElementContainerRetains`
// makes the container take its own ref.
function resultConsumedByContainer(module StdModule, func IrFunction, resultId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("resultConsumedByContainer: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("resultConsumedByContainer: opIdx not in module.ops")
			// `callConsumesManagedElement` (the inserter's container-mutator consume
			// recognizer) is the single source of truth for "is this op a container
			// mutator consuming `resultId` as an element?" — shared here so the
			// borrow-reclassification narrowing stays in lockstep with the inserter's
			// `planBorrowedElementContainerRetains` consume set. Both read the same
			// structural `project.funcParamConsumes` bits computed by
			// `analyzeParamConsumes` (Concept C).
			if callConsumesManagedElement(project.funcParamConsumes, op: op, argId: resultId) 'consumed'
				return true
			end 'consumed'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'resultConsumedByContainer'

// The result ValueId of `op` iff `op` is a direct/try call to a borrow-returning
// callee, else `none`.
function borrowReturningCallResult(op StdOp, project Project) returns RetValueOpt
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith gives RetValueOpt.none()
		control gives RetValueOpt.none()
		call(c) gives borrowReturningCallResultOfCall(c, project: project)
		memory gives RetValueOpt.none()
		system gives RetValueOpt.none()
	end 'dispatch'
end 'borrowReturningCallResult'

function borrowReturningCallResultOfCall(c StdCallOp, project Project) returns RetValueOpt
	return match c 'check'
		ret gives RetValueOpt.none()
		call(resultId, callee, _) gives (RetValueOpt.some(resultId) if calleeReturnsBorrow(callee, project: project) else RetValueOpt.none())
		tryCall(resultId, callee, _, _) gives (RetValueOpt.some(resultId) if calleeReturnsBorrow(callee, project: project) else RetValueOpt.none())
		indirectCall to tailCall gives RetValueOpt.none()
		param gives RetValueOpt.none()
		errorReturn gives RetValueOpt.none()
	end 'check'
end 'borrowReturningCallResultOfCall'

// Per-function map from a ValueId to the index of the op that DEFINES it (its
// `writeIds`). Built once per function for the return-value provenance walk.
typealias ValueDefMap = Map with (ValueId, OpIndex)

function buildValueDefMap(module StdModule, func IrFunction) returns ValueDefMap
	var defs = ValueDefMap.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("buildValueDefMap: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("buildValueDefMap: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
			for writeId in operands.writeIds 'eachDef'
				defs.upsert(writeId, value: opIdx)
			end 'eachDef'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return defs
end 'buildValueDefMap'
